name: Predator: an open source performance testing platform for APIs
description:
Predator is a performance testing platform for APIs. It manages the entire lifecycle of load testing APIs, from creating and managing existing performance tests, to running these tests on a scheduled and on-demand basis, and finally viewing the test results in a highly informative and live built-in report.

Predator has a simple, one-click installation, built with support for Kubernetes (helm charts), DC/OS (mesosphere universe), and Docker Engine, and can persist the created performance tests and their reports in 5 different databases. It also supports running distributed load out of the box, enabling an unlimited amount of virtual users that can bombard your servers. Bootstrapped with a user-friendly UI alongside a simple REST API, Predator helps developers simplify the performance testing regime.

https://zooz.github.io/predator/images/predator-screens.gif

report_tracker_justification: Issues are tracked via GitHub issues, as documented in  https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md.
report_process_justification: Bug reports are filed via GitHub issues, as documented in  https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md.
report_responses_justification: The project uses GitHub Issue labels to acknowledge the priority of incoming issues, as described in  https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md. Priorities are reviewed regularly by the TSC. Over 100 issues have been closed in the last 6 months.
enhancement_responses_justification: All outstanding enhancements requests are prioritized, with priorities indicated via GitHub Issue labels. Priorities are reviewed regularly by the TSC. Over 100 pull requests have been merged in the last 6 months.
report_archive_justification: Issues are tracked via GitHub issues and pull requests, as documented in  https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md. Also, the email list openexr-dev@lists.aswf.io is archived and searchable.
vulnerability_report_process_justificati: Vulnerabilities may be reported as GitHub issues or via email to security@openexr.com, as documented in https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/SECURITY.md.
vulnerability_report_private_justificati: Vulnerabilities may be reported via email to security@openexr.com, accessible only to the OpenEXR TSC, as documented in https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/SECURITY.md.
vulnerability_report_response_justificat: The project policy is to respond to vulnerability reports within 14 days, as described in https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/SECURITY.md
build_justification: Build is via either CMake or Gnu autotools, as documented in https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/INSTALL.md.
build_common_tools_justification: Build is via either CMake or Gnu autotools, as documented in https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/INSTALL.md.
build_floss_tools_justification: Build is via either CMake or Gnu autotools, as documented in https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/INSTALL.md.
test_justification: The GitHub repo includes companion test suites, executable via ctest, for all project libraries (IlmBase, IlmBasePy, OpenEXR, OpenEXR_Viewers).
test_most_justification:
Current tests coverage is approximately 80%, reported by SonarCloud: https://sonarcloud.io/organizations/openexr-github/projects. 
The project testing policy is described in https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md.
tests_are_added_justification: The most recent changes to the library have been bug fixes, many identified by failures in the test suite, including fuzz testing. No major features have been added in several years. SonarCloud reports that test coverage is above 80% of the library.
warnings_justification: Compilation uses the strictest C++ warning flags, and "linting" is via SonarCloud.
warnings_fixed_justification: The project compiles cleanly, without warnings from g++ and clang.
warnings_strict_justification: Compilation is with the strictest gcc/clang warning options.
know_secure_design_justification: The project committers are experienced C++ programmers knowledgeable about issues such as buffer overflow, memory access, etc. In addition, the ASWF TAC is available to identify security industry experts to consult on specific issues.
know_common_errors_justification: The project committers are experienced C++ programmers knowledgeable about issues such as buffer overflow, memory access, etc.  The project implements no cryptography or security-sensitive functionality.
crypto_floss_justification: OpenEXR performs no cryptographic functions, and all software is covered by FLOSS.
delivery_unsigned_justification: Web site and GitHub repo use https, and the library does not implement any cryptographic hashing.
vulnerabilities_fixed_60_days_justificat: The most recent 2.4.0 release addresses all publicly know security vulnerabilities.
vulnerabilities_critical_fixed_justifica: The project's stated security policy is to address vulnerabilities as rapidly as possible after they are reported, as documented in https://github.com/openexr/openexr/blob/master/SECURITY.md
static_analysis_justification: The project uses SonarCloud: https://sonarcloud.io/organizations/openexr-github/projects. Analysis runs are triggered by each PR.
static_analysis_common_vulnerabilities_j: The project uses SonarCloud, which detects common vulnerabilities: https://sonarcloud.io/organizations/openexr-github/projects
static_analysis_fixed_justification: All known vulnerabilities have been addressed, and the project's posted security policy is to address all reported vulnerabilities in a timely manner.
static_analysis_often_justification: The project uses SonarCloud: https://sonarcloud.io/organizations/openexr-github/projects. Analysis runs are triggered by each PR.
dynamic_analysis_justification: "make valgrind" runs valgrind on each of the project's unit tests. The policy is to run this periodically, and before each release.
dynamic_analysis_unsafe_justification: "make valgrind" runs valgrind on each of the project's unit tests. Also, the IlmImfFuzzTest unit test is an extensive fuzz test suite. Also, the Google Fuzz project intermittently run the Google AutoFuzz tester on the project and reports issues via GitHub.
dynamic_analysis_enable_assertions_justi: The project includes a comprehensive test suite, including fuzz tests that validate behavior on corrupted or maliciously-constructed input data.
dynamic_analysis_fixed_justification: All known vulnerabilities have been addressed, and the project's posted security policy is to address all reported vulnerabilities in a timely manner.
test_continuous_integration_justificatio: Continuous integration via Azure pipelines: https://dev.azure.com/openexr/. Builds are triggered on each PR.
discussion_justification: OpenEXR supports discussions via GitHub issues and pull requests, as well as via the openexr-dev@lists.aswf.io mail group.
no_leaked_credentials_justification: The library does not make use of any private credentials.
crypto_used_network_justification: The project uses no network communication.
crypto_tls12_justification: The project uses no network communication.
crypto_certificate_verification_justific: The project uses no network communication.
crypto_verification_private_justificatio: The project uses no network communication.
hardened_site_justification: // X-Content-Type-Options was not set to "nosniff".
dco_justification: Project uses the LF EasyCLA system and requires DCO on all commits, enforced through automated GitHub checks. https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/settings/installations
governance_justification: Project governance is documented in the main repo: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/blob/master/GOVERNANCE.md
code_of_conduct_justification: Project code of conduct is documented in the main repo: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/blob/master/CODE_OF_CONDUCT.md
roles_responsibilities_justification: Roles and responsibilities are documented in the main repo: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/blob/master/GOVERNANCE.md
access_continuity_justification: The project has no private keys beyond GitHub repo administrator permissions, administered by the LF.
documentation_architecture_justification: Extensive technical documentation is maintained in the main GitHub repo: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/tree/master/docs
documentation_achievements_justification: Main repo page displays the CII badge: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr
sites_password_security_justification: OpenEXR stores no passwords or authentication credentials.
maintenance_or_update_justification: Patches are provided to several widely used older releases (v2.4, v2.5, v3.0)
vulnerability_report_credit_justificatio:
Issues identified via OSS-Fuzz reference the oss-fuzz issue page. 

No other vulnerabilities have been reported in the last 12 months.
vulnerability_response_process_justifica: Security policy is documented in the main repo: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/blob/master/SECURITY.md
coding_standards_justification: Coding style guidelines are documented in the main repo: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#coding-style
build_standard_variables_justification: The project CMake settings do not override external settings.
build_preserve_debug_justification: The project CMake settings do not override debugging information
build_non_recursive_justification: There are no cross-dependencies between subprojects.
installation_standard_variables_justific: Installation directory is provided via a CMake setting.
installation_development_quick_justifica: The project CMake setup generates an "install" step.
external_dependencies_justification: External dependencies are documented in the CMake setup: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/blob/master/cmake/OpenEXRSetup.cmake
interfaces_current_justification: OpenEXR's on external dependency is Zlib, the standard compression algorithm. Imath depends on boost and python and regularly updates to the latest revisions.
automated_integration_testing_justificat: The project uses GitHub Actions to invoke the test suite on each PR. The project is also integrated with OSS-Fuzz, which runs continuously against the latest development branch.
test_policy_mandated_justification: Test policy is documented in the main repo: https://github.com/AcademySoftwareFoundation/openexr/blob/master/CONTRIBUTING.md#test-policy
crypto_credential_agility_justification: The project stores no authentication credentials.

name: DEploid
